<section xmlns="http://xml.house.gov/schemas/uslm/1.0" style="-uslm-lc:I80" id="idb99ad4ab-47c4-11f1-9a61-b1559996dfe8" identifier="/us/usc/t18/s3290"><num value="3290">§ 3290.</num><heading> Fugitives from justice</heading><content>
<p style="-uslm-lc:I11" class="indent0">No statute of limitations shall extend to any person fleeing from justice.</p>
</content><sourceCredit id="idb99ad4ac-47c4-11f1-9a61-b1559996dfe8">(<ref href="/us/act/1948-06-25/ch645">June 25, 1948, ch. 645</ref>, <ref href="/us/stat/62/829">62 Stat. 829</ref>.)</sourceCredit>
<notes type="uscNote" id="idb99ad4ad-47c4-11f1-9a61-b1559996dfe8">
<note style="-uslm-lc:I74" topic="historicalAndRevision" id="idb99ad4ae-47c4-11f1-9a61-b1559996dfe8"><heading class="centered smallCaps">Historical and Revision Notes</heading><p style="-uslm-lc:I21" class="indent0">Based on Title 18, U.S.C., 1940 ed., § 583 (R.S. § 1045).</p>
<p style="-uslm-lc:I21" class="indent0">Said section 583 was rephrased and made applicable to all statutes of limitation and is merely declaratory of the generally accepted rule of law.</p>
</note>
</notes>
</section>
